sections:
  0. the-page-that-answers-itself [36mcinematic[0m/xl  Open with the exact artifact Kettle produces: a deploy timeline showing a change, a red status, and a name — before any claim is made.
  1. 3am-problem      [36meditorial[0m/md  Name the real cost: a small team's service breaks, nobody knows what shipped, and the on-call engineer is guessing instead of fixing.
  2. what-changed     [36masymmetric[0m/lg  Show the before/after: a raw commit list on one side, Kettle's annotated timeline (who deployed, what changed, blast radius) on the other.
  3. what-broke       [36mnarrative[0m/lg  Demonstrate the alerting/diagnosis flow: an incident is detected, correlated to the deploy that caused it, and routed to the right person automatically.
  4. who-to-ask       [36mmodular[0m/md  Show ownership mapping as a concrete grid: which services, which teams, which humans — so accountability is visible before an incident, not during one.
  5. proof-in-the-wild [36meditorial[0m/sm  Build trust progressively with a specific engineering team's account of catching a bad deploy in minutes instead of hours.
  6. free-for-three   [36meditorial[0m/md  State the concrete offer plainly: free for up to 3 services, transparent pricing beyond that, no sales call required to start.
  7. start-watching   [36meditorial[0m/sm  Single clear call to connect a repo and see the first deploy timeline populate — the natural next step after proof, not a generic sign-up pitch.
  8. how-it-works     [36meditorial[0m/md  show the tool actually being used — a real, runnable example, not a description of one
  9. ask              [36meditorial[0m/md  point to documentation or installation as the next step

